Advisory teachers present at the session identified ways in which they could make use of the outcomes of the project.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>54da288042b784.03647973</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>7580</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>International Partnership and Mobility Scheme</gtr:description><gtr:end>2013-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>The British Academy</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>261EE5C0-AB60-4FEA-AF55-A7BF0784348C</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5457a5725aa291.57041513</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2012-09-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>This project aimed to impact on policy and practices of those responsible for setting examinations and on teachers preparing school pupils to take examinations.
At the level of policy and the practice of examination boards, evidence of impact is hard to identify as there have been a number of policy changes motivated by other sources. Having said that, current changes in mathematics examinations are consistent with the recommendations of the project, including less trivial engagement with mathematics in context and less structured questions that demand more agency on the part of students. Recently (November 2016), following publication of journal articles arising from the project, we have been approached by one of the examination boards with a view to using the analytic framework developed in the project in order to evaluate specimen papers developed for the new GCSE and GCE specifications. This consultancy is still under negotiation.
At the level of the practice of mathematics teachers, there is some anecdotal evidence of impact on the practices of those teachers, advisory teachers and teacher educators who have been directly involved in dissemination events. This has included use with students of examples shared at dissemination events and more general use of strategies discussed at these events. 
Outcomes of the research have continued to be disseminated to teaching practitioners. This dissemination has occurred directly through interventions with Initial Teacher Education trainees at the Institute of Education (June 2014) and an invited presentation at the annual conferences of the National Association of Mathematics Advisors (March 2014). Dissemination also occurs indirectly by informing the practices of mathematics teacher educators who have attended academic seminars (e.g. University of Nottingham, April 2014; University of Cambridge, October 2014).</gtr:description><gtr:id>384CDD21-5133-4CEA-9F6C-651A148B31AC</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54da230ca476f9.15266939</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>A framework for analysing school mathematics discourse as found in student tasks and other texts addressed to pupils (e.g. textbooks, examinations).</gtr:description><gtr:id>75E23BB4-D925-490E-B50F-D1E3C1FE779B</gtr:id><gtr:impact>An adaptation of the model has been applied to the analysis of mathematics textbooks in Palestine.
